In mid-July, 1988's drought was predicted to continue three months. Severe storms 
brought tornadoes, hail damage, and lightning-sparked fires. States issued heat alerts. 
Weather experts attended a Drought Symposium. Grain futures and certain jobs fell. Hay 
was transported for free. Aid, loans, and reduced controls for farmers were proposed.  
Drinking water was short. Livestock sales increased.</SUM> 
